1
00:00:00,190 --> 00:00:01,990
A warm greeting to you as we begin.

2
00:00:02,890 --> 00:00:06,050
We are stepping back into Ayyuhal Walad, Imam

3
00:00:06,050 --> 00:00:08,490
al-Ghazali's famous letter to a former student,

4
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:10,270
for the second part of our five-part

5
00:00:10,270 --> 00:00:10,650
series.

6
00:00:11,510 --> 00:00:14,110
This chapter holds the single most quoted story

7
00:00:14,110 --> 00:00:17,570
in the entire letter, a master asking his

8
00:00:17,570 --> 00:00:20,470
devoted disciple of 33 years what he has

9
00:00:20,470 --> 00:00:23,270
actually learned, and the answer to that question

10
00:00:23,270 --> 00:00:26,010
will challenge everything we think we know about

11
00:00:26,010 --> 00:00:27,190
the accumulation of knowledge.

12
00:00:27,190 --> 00:00:28,490
It really does challenge everything.

13
00:00:29,130 --> 00:00:30,910
And to set the stage for you, we

14
00:00:30,910 --> 00:00:33,150
need to look at these two towering figures

15
00:00:33,150 --> 00:00:36,070
in the spiritual landscape of 8th century Khorasan.

16
00:00:36,610 --> 00:00:39,430
So the master is Shaqiq al-Balki, who

17
00:00:39,430 --> 00:00:41,990
is a man of immense authority and just

18
00:00:41,990 --> 00:00:43,550
a profound inner life.

19
00:00:43,630 --> 00:00:45,750
And his student is Hatim bin Ism al

20
00:00:45,750 --> 00:00:46,110
-Assam.

21
00:00:46,270 --> 00:00:47,390
Yeah, Hatim had been with him for a

22
00:00:47,390 --> 00:00:48,150
really long time, right?

23
00:00:48,210 --> 00:00:48,850
Yeah, exactly.

24
00:00:48,990 --> 00:00:51,170
He spent over three decades by his teacher's

25
00:00:51,170 --> 00:00:51,410
side.

26
00:00:51,730 --> 00:00:53,750
So the story actually begins with a question

27
00:00:53,750 --> 00:00:55,510
that carries the weight of all those years.

28
00:00:55,990 --> 00:00:58,450
Shaqiq turns to Hatim and he asks, Oh,

29
00:00:58,470 --> 00:01:00,090
Hatim, how long have you been in my

30
00:01:00,090 --> 00:01:01,670
company and listen to what I've been saying?

31
00:01:01,870 --> 00:01:03,450
Which is, I mean, it's quite the setup

32
00:01:03,450 --> 00:01:04,550
for a performance review.

33
00:01:04,910 --> 00:01:05,650
It really is.

34
00:01:06,090 --> 00:01:08,990
And Hatim replies that it has been 33

35
00:01:08,990 --> 00:01:09,550
years.

36
00:01:10,010 --> 00:01:11,270
So Shaqiq presses him.

37
00:01:11,610 --> 00:01:14,850
He asks, in all that time, what benefit

38
00:01:14,850 --> 00:01:16,150
have you derived from me?

39
00:01:16,590 --> 00:01:17,610
33 years of studying.

40
00:01:17,810 --> 00:01:20,010
You would expect a massive catalog of knowledge.

41
00:01:20,110 --> 00:01:20,250
Right.

42
00:01:20,330 --> 00:01:22,310
But Hatim just answers that he has obtained

43
00:01:22,310 --> 00:01:23,530
eight benefits.

44
00:01:23,690 --> 00:01:24,170
Just eight.

45
00:01:24,770 --> 00:01:26,850
And, you know, the reaction from the teacher

46
00:01:26,850 --> 00:01:28,950
is what makes this moment so arresting.

47
00:01:29,010 --> 00:01:30,910
He doesn't like ask to hear them right

48
00:01:30,910 --> 00:01:31,250
away.

49
00:01:31,370 --> 00:01:33,370
And he certainly doesn't praise his student's brevity.

50
00:01:33,650 --> 00:01:36,670
Shaqiq experiences this profound, immediate grief.

51
00:01:36,850 --> 00:01:38,110
He is completely shattered.

52
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:40,750
He actually recites the Quranic verse that Muslims

53
00:01:40,750 --> 00:01:43,750
utter at moments of devastating loss, like when

54
00:01:43,750 --> 00:01:45,470
someone has died or a tragedy has struck.

55
00:01:45,630 --> 00:01:48,270
He says, Indeed, to Allah we belong and

56
00:01:48,270 --> 00:01:49,430
to him we shall return.

57
00:01:49,630 --> 00:01:50,110
Oh, wow.

58
00:01:50,290 --> 00:01:51,350
So he's literally mourning.

59
00:01:51,570 --> 00:01:51,890
Yes.

60
00:01:51,890 --> 00:01:53,810
He looks at his devoted student and says,

61
00:01:54,030 --> 00:01:55,930
Oh, Hatim, I have spent my lifetime teaching

62
00:01:55,930 --> 00:01:58,110
you and you have just gained eight benefits

63
00:01:58,110 --> 00:01:58,530
from me.

64
00:01:58,730 --> 00:02:01,090
He believes the student has gained tragically little

65
00:02:01,090 --> 00:02:03,290
from a lifetime of rigorous spiritual work.

66
00:02:03,410 --> 00:02:06,850
But Hatim, he remains incredibly calm through all

67
00:02:06,850 --> 00:02:07,130
this.

68
00:02:07,430 --> 00:02:09,870
He doesn't apologize and he doesn't, you know,

69
00:02:10,250 --> 00:02:13,750
scramble to invent more benefits just to appease

70
00:02:13,750 --> 00:02:14,710
his master's grief.

71
00:02:14,890 --> 00:02:15,750
No, not at all.

72
00:02:15,850 --> 00:02:19,110
He simply states, without flinching, that these eight

73
00:02:19,110 --> 00:02:20,050
are the reality.

74
00:02:20,050 --> 00:02:22,270
He tells Shaqiq, I do not need more.

75
00:02:22,710 --> 00:02:24,290
These eight are enough to carry me through

76
00:02:24,290 --> 00:02:25,470
this life and into the next.

77
00:02:25,610 --> 00:02:26,670
Yeah, it's such a bold claim.

78
00:02:26,990 --> 00:02:27,310
It is.

79
00:02:27,430 --> 00:02:29,770
And it makes you wonder, who is right

80
00:02:29,770 --> 00:02:30,130
here?

81
00:02:30,970 --> 00:02:32,630
I mean, the teacher who sees a tragedy

82
00:02:32,630 --> 00:02:34,970
of wasted time or the student who claims

83
00:02:34,970 --> 00:02:37,250
absolute sufficiency in just eight things.

84
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:40,210
We're going to leave that question completely unresolved

85
00:02:40,210 --> 00:02:40,910
for you to ponder.

86
00:02:41,190 --> 00:02:42,070
It's a heavy question.

87
00:02:42,230 --> 00:02:44,490
But eventually the master does invite him to

88
00:02:44,490 --> 00:02:45,670
name these eight benefits.

89
00:02:45,670 --> 00:02:48,230
And when Hatim begins to speak, he reveals

90
00:02:48,230 --> 00:02:51,310
something far more profound than just a simple

91
00:02:51,310 --> 00:02:53,150
list of theological bullet points.

92
00:02:53,490 --> 00:02:55,650
It's actually a rigorous, repeated discipline, isn't it?

93
00:02:55,810 --> 00:02:57,510
The structure he uses is a method, not

94
00:02:57,510 --> 00:02:58,090
just a sermon.

95
00:02:58,230 --> 00:02:58,570
Exactly.

96
00:02:58,850 --> 00:03:01,370
For every single benefit, Hatim does the exact

97
00:03:01,370 --> 00:03:01,970
same thing.

98
00:03:02,090 --> 00:03:03,730
He observes the people of the world.

99
00:03:04,110 --> 00:03:05,170
He sees what they value.

100
00:03:05,450 --> 00:03:07,770
And then he realizes that those worldly values

101
00:03:07,770 --> 00:03:09,250
inevitably fail.

102
00:03:09,470 --> 00:03:09,650
Right.

103
00:03:09,710 --> 00:03:11,010
He sees the cracks in the system.

104
00:03:11,090 --> 00:03:11,370
Yes.

105
00:03:11,370 --> 00:03:14,030
And then he meditates on a specific Quranic

106
00:03:14,030 --> 00:03:16,930
verse that provides the eternal alternative.

107
00:03:17,710 --> 00:03:20,630
And finally, he radically reorganizes his life around

108
00:03:20,630 --> 00:03:21,150
that verse.

109
00:03:21,830 --> 00:03:24,790
He applied this deliberate structural dismantling of illusion

110
00:03:24,790 --> 00:03:27,010
eight times over those 33 years.

111
00:03:27,290 --> 00:03:29,850
And the very first illusion he dismantles is

112
00:03:29,850 --> 00:03:31,610
the concept of the beloved.

113
00:03:31,890 --> 00:03:32,150
Yeah.

114
00:03:32,310 --> 00:03:33,050
The first pivot.

115
00:03:33,570 --> 00:03:35,190
Hatim says he looked around and saw that

116
00:03:35,190 --> 00:03:37,490
everyone has something or someone they love.

117
00:03:37,590 --> 00:03:40,250
You know, a spouse, a friend, wealth, honor,

118
00:03:40,590 --> 00:03:40,910
status.

119
00:03:40,910 --> 00:03:43,250
But he noticed a brutal timeline attached to

120
00:03:43,250 --> 00:03:43,750
all of them, right?

121
00:03:43,950 --> 00:03:44,250
He did.

122
00:03:44,510 --> 00:03:46,390
He noticed that some of these beloveds stay

123
00:03:46,390 --> 00:03:48,250
with the lover until an illness arrives.

124
00:03:48,710 --> 00:03:50,090
Some stay until the moment of death.

125
00:03:50,410 --> 00:03:51,870
Some might even stay until the burial.

126
00:03:52,410 --> 00:03:54,550
But after the grave is closed, the lovers

127
00:03:54,550 --> 00:03:55,350
all go home.

128
00:03:55,710 --> 00:03:58,650
The bond is real, but the departure is

129
00:03:58,650 --> 00:03:59,110
absolute.

130
00:03:59,550 --> 00:04:02,130
None of these worldly beloveds actually enter the

131
00:04:02,130 --> 00:04:03,510
grave with the one who loved them.

132
00:04:03,890 --> 00:04:04,370
Exactly.

133
00:04:04,770 --> 00:04:07,290
So, Hatim decided to find the only beloved

134
00:04:07,290 --> 00:04:09,210
that possessed the qualities he demanded.

135
00:04:09,610 --> 00:04:11,330
He wanted a beloved that would go with

136
00:04:11,330 --> 00:04:13,190
him into the grave, keep him company there,

137
00:04:13,350 --> 00:04:15,250
illuminate the darkness, stand beside him on the

138
00:04:15,250 --> 00:04:17,149
day of judgment, and just never leave.

139
00:04:17,350 --> 00:04:18,890
And what did he find that met those

140
00:04:18,890 --> 00:04:19,370
criteria?

141
00:04:20,010 --> 00:04:21,870
He realized the only thing that meets those

142
00:04:21,870 --> 00:04:24,050
criteria is his own good deeds.

143
00:04:24,730 --> 00:04:27,230
So he made his righteous actions his beloved.

144
00:04:27,770 --> 00:04:30,610
He gave his daily conduct the affection, attention,

145
00:04:30,830 --> 00:04:33,490
and loyalty that human beings normally reserve for

146
00:04:33,490 --> 00:04:33,950
a person.

147
00:04:34,470 --> 00:04:36,370
That is just a complete inversion of how

148
00:04:36,370 --> 00:04:37,750
we normally think about legacy.

149
00:04:37,750 --> 00:04:40,070
I mean, we usually define our legacy as

150
00:04:40,070 --> 00:04:41,390
a monument we build.

151
00:04:41,530 --> 00:04:43,410
It's the company we founded, the inheritance we

152
00:04:43,410 --> 00:04:45,570
pass on, or the memories other people hold

153
00:04:45,570 --> 00:04:45,850
of us.

154
00:04:45,870 --> 00:04:47,710
It's what we leave behind, you know, in

155
00:04:47,710 --> 00:04:48,590
the rearview mirror.

156
00:04:48,810 --> 00:04:48,990
Right.

157
00:04:49,290 --> 00:04:51,930
But Hatim looks at legacy as luggage.

158
00:04:52,930 --> 00:04:53,870
It is what you pack.

159
00:04:54,130 --> 00:04:55,250
It is what goes with you.

160
00:04:55,670 --> 00:04:57,830
And that concept is deeply grounded in the

161
00:04:57,830 --> 00:04:58,790
tradition, isn't it?

162
00:04:58,910 --> 00:04:59,410
It is.

163
00:04:59,510 --> 00:05:01,270
It's grounded in the teachings of the prophet

164
00:05:01,270 --> 00:05:03,810
Muhammad, who explained that when a person dies,

165
00:05:04,330 --> 00:05:06,090
their actions come to an end except for

166
00:05:06,090 --> 00:05:06,710
three things.

167
00:05:07,330 --> 00:05:10,510
A continuing charity, a beneficial knowledge, and a

168
00:05:10,510 --> 00:05:11,910
pious child who prays for them.

169
00:05:12,190 --> 00:05:14,570
So all three of those surviving entities are,

170
00:05:14,730 --> 00:05:16,230
in themselves, actions.

171
00:05:16,710 --> 00:05:18,290
They are the things you did that keep

172
00:05:18,290 --> 00:05:19,630
echoing after you were gone.

173
00:05:19,690 --> 00:05:20,450
Yeah, exactly.

174
00:05:20,870 --> 00:05:23,490
But making your actions your ultimate beloved creates

175
00:05:23,490 --> 00:05:25,070
an immediate internal war.

176
00:05:25,590 --> 00:05:27,870
The moment you decide to focus entirely on

177
00:05:27,870 --> 00:05:31,210
good deeds, your lower appetites scream for attention

178
00:05:31,210 --> 00:05:33,070
because they want to be loved instead.

179
00:05:33,070 --> 00:05:34,730
And that brings us to the second benefit,

180
00:05:34,950 --> 00:05:35,110
right?

181
00:05:35,270 --> 00:05:37,190
How he dealt with that internal war.

182
00:05:37,290 --> 00:05:37,550
Yes.

183
00:05:37,830 --> 00:05:40,330
In the Sufi technical vocabulary, this appetite is

184
00:05:40,330 --> 00:05:42,210
called the nafs, the lower soul.

185
00:05:42,850 --> 00:05:44,590
It's the part of the human psychology that

186
00:05:44,590 --> 00:05:46,150
pulls toward base desires.

187
00:05:46,830 --> 00:05:49,310
It wants comfort, status, and pleasure right now,

188
00:05:49,490 --> 00:05:51,670
regardless of the long-term spiritual cost.

189
00:05:51,770 --> 00:05:53,090
It's the part of us that just wants

190
00:05:53,090 --> 00:05:53,650
to consume.

191
00:05:54,170 --> 00:05:54,650
Exactly.

192
00:05:54,930 --> 00:05:57,870
And Hatim realized that most people were completely

193
00:05:57,870 --> 00:06:00,030
subservient to their lower soul.

194
00:06:00,430 --> 00:06:02,510
They believed they were acting in freedom because

195
00:06:02,510 --> 00:06:04,430
they were doing what they wanted, but they

196
00:06:04,430 --> 00:06:07,190
were actually just obeying their unexamined appetites.

197
00:06:07,370 --> 00:06:08,890
Okay, I have to jump in here because

198
00:06:08,890 --> 00:06:12,790
our modern culture is built entirely around concepts

199
00:06:12,790 --> 00:06:14,710
that validate those appetites.

200
00:06:14,790 --> 00:06:15,430
Oh, absolutely.

201
00:06:15,730 --> 00:06:19,130
We talk constantly about finding balance, practicing self

202
00:06:19,130 --> 00:06:20,610
-care, honoring our desires.

203
00:06:20,990 --> 00:06:23,890
We're basically told that denying ourselves is unhealthy.

204
00:06:24,670 --> 00:06:27,710
So Hatim's response sounds incredibly harsh to the

205
00:06:27,710 --> 00:06:29,610
modern ear, almost cruel, honestly.

206
00:06:29,610 --> 00:06:30,630
I know it sounds harsh.

207
00:06:30,850 --> 00:06:33,090
He establishes a front against his lower soul,

208
00:06:33,250 --> 00:06:35,370
and he refuses to fulfill any of its

209
00:06:35,370 --> 00:06:35,810
desires.

210
00:06:36,090 --> 00:06:37,570
He does not negotiate with it.

211
00:06:37,850 --> 00:06:39,930
He starved it of every yes until it

212
00:06:39,930 --> 00:06:41,630
found peace in the worship of God.

213
00:06:41,690 --> 00:06:43,050
He just completely shut it down.

214
00:06:43,110 --> 00:06:43,770
No compromise.

215
00:06:44,030 --> 00:06:44,330
None.

216
00:06:44,690 --> 00:06:47,030
Because he recognized that negotiation with the lower

217
00:06:47,030 --> 00:06:48,310
soul always fails.

218
00:06:48,890 --> 00:06:51,150
Imam Ali captured the mechanics of this failure

219
00:06:51,150 --> 00:06:53,090
brilliantly when he taught, do not let the

220
00:06:53,090 --> 00:06:54,770
lower soul be a partner in your decisions.

221
00:06:54,850 --> 00:06:56,310
It speaks in your own voice, so you

222
00:06:56,310 --> 00:06:57,410
will not notice its arguments.

223
00:06:57,890 --> 00:06:58,190
Wow.

224
00:06:58,690 --> 00:07:00,010
It speaks in your own voice.

225
00:07:00,570 --> 00:07:01,790
So if you try to strike a bargain

226
00:07:01,790 --> 00:07:04,010
with your appetite, giving it half of what

227
00:07:04,010 --> 00:07:05,930
it wants just to keep it quiet, you're

228
00:07:05,930 --> 00:07:06,390
going to lose.

229
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:06,930
You will lose.

230
00:07:07,030 --> 00:07:07,230
Yes.

231
00:07:07,450 --> 00:07:10,150
It uses your own logic, your own internal

232
00:07:10,150 --> 00:07:12,870
monologue to convince you that a compromise is

233
00:07:12,870 --> 00:07:13,670
actually a victory.

234
00:07:14,110 --> 00:07:16,650
So Hatim simply refused to participate in the

235
00:07:16,650 --> 00:07:17,170
negotiation.

236
00:07:17,630 --> 00:07:19,270
And the loudest thing that the lower soul

237
00:07:19,270 --> 00:07:22,910
usually demands from us is security, which almost

238
00:07:22,910 --> 00:07:24,250
always means accumulation.

239
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:26,350
And that leads to his third observation.

240
00:07:26,550 --> 00:07:26,810
Right.

241
00:07:26,810 --> 00:07:29,370
Hatim saw people working with great pain to

242
00:07:29,370 --> 00:07:31,650
accumulate the possessions of this mortal world.

243
00:07:32,070 --> 00:07:34,630
People derive a massive sense of happiness and

244
00:07:34,630 --> 00:07:37,010
safety from having a stockpile of resources.

245
00:07:37,310 --> 00:07:39,570
But he meditates on a Quranic verse that

246
00:07:39,570 --> 00:07:41,970
completely redefines the nature of a stockpile, doesn't

247
00:07:41,970 --> 00:07:42,110
he?

248
00:07:42,190 --> 00:07:42,670
He does.

249
00:07:42,990 --> 00:07:44,850
The verse states, all that is with you

250
00:07:44,850 --> 00:07:46,150
is bound to come to an end.

251
00:07:46,570 --> 00:07:48,690
All that which is with Allah is everlasting.

252
00:07:49,850 --> 00:07:52,110
So Hatim changed the physical location where he

253
00:07:52,110 --> 00:07:53,070
stored his earnings.

254
00:07:53,330 --> 00:07:54,390
What does that look like practically?

255
00:07:54,390 --> 00:07:56,550
He took whatever wealth he had accumulated and

256
00:07:56,550 --> 00:07:57,750
distributed it to the destitute.

257
00:07:58,150 --> 00:08:00,690
He basically deposited his wealth with God rather

258
00:08:00,690 --> 00:08:02,130
than leaving it behind in the dust.

259
00:08:02,490 --> 00:08:04,370
Which connects perfectly to what the Prophet Muhammad

260
00:08:04,370 --> 00:08:06,550
taught, that your wealth is only what you

261
00:08:06,550 --> 00:08:08,550
ate, what you wore, and what you gave

262
00:08:08,550 --> 00:08:08,850
away.

263
00:08:09,290 --> 00:08:11,170
Everything else in your bank account isn't really

264
00:08:11,170 --> 00:08:11,530
yours.

265
00:08:11,950 --> 00:08:14,130
You're just holding it for whoever inherits it

266
00:08:14,130 --> 00:08:14,530
next.

267
00:08:14,730 --> 00:08:16,290
That's a sobering thought, isn't it?

268
00:08:16,510 --> 00:08:19,370
And functionally, giving away your wealth without becoming

269
00:08:19,370 --> 00:08:21,950
destitute yourself requires a massive shift in how

270
00:08:21,950 --> 00:08:23,050
you measure value.

271
00:08:23,050 --> 00:08:23,510
Yeah.

272
00:08:23,810 --> 00:08:26,850
Because once you stop accumulating money just to

273
00:08:26,850 --> 00:08:29,710
hoard it, you realize money is usually just

274
00:08:29,710 --> 00:08:32,110
a proxy for something else, which is status.

275
00:08:32,669 --> 00:08:33,690
And that's the fourth pivot.

276
00:08:33,909 --> 00:08:34,409
Exactly.

277
00:08:35,010 --> 00:08:37,770
Hatim observes people desperately trying to claim grandeur

278
00:08:37,770 --> 00:08:38,270
and honor.

279
00:08:38,690 --> 00:08:40,830
They use large tribes or social networks as

280
00:08:40,830 --> 00:08:41,530
a scoreboard.

281
00:08:41,789 --> 00:08:42,470
They use wealth.

282
00:08:42,929 --> 00:08:45,790
Some use violence, anger, and intimidation to feel

283
00:08:45,790 --> 00:08:46,370
powerful.

284
00:08:46,610 --> 00:08:49,370
Some even take pride in lavish waste, signaling

285
00:08:49,370 --> 00:08:51,090
their worth by how much they can afford

286
00:08:51,090 --> 00:08:52,790
to destroy or just throw away.

287
00:08:52,970 --> 00:08:53,190
Right.

288
00:08:53,950 --> 00:08:56,190
Hatim looked at all those mechanisms for claiming

289
00:08:56,190 --> 00:08:58,910
honor and anchored himself instead to taqwa.

290
00:08:59,550 --> 00:09:00,530
God-consciousness.

291
00:09:00,890 --> 00:09:01,150
Yes.

292
00:09:01,630 --> 00:09:03,930
The Quran says, Indeed, the most honored of

293
00:09:03,930 --> 00:09:05,190
you in the sight of Allah is the

294
00:09:05,190 --> 00:09:07,210
one who is most deeply conscious of him.

295
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:11,230
Taqwa is this watchful, constant awareness of God's

296
00:09:11,230 --> 00:09:11,550
presence.

297
00:09:12,210 --> 00:09:14,010
It dictates how you act when the doors

298
00:09:14,010 --> 00:09:15,890
are closed, when there is no audience, and

299
00:09:15,890 --> 00:09:17,190
when no one is keeping score.

300
00:09:17,190 --> 00:09:20,030
Because none of those worldly candidates for honor,

301
00:09:20,310 --> 00:09:23,050
you know, bloodline, money, force, or showing off,

302
00:09:23,210 --> 00:09:24,730
they have nothing to do with reality.

303
00:09:24,770 --> 00:09:25,390
Nothing at all.

304
00:09:25,510 --> 00:09:27,750
And this insight echoes across the centuries.

305
00:09:28,470 --> 00:09:31,470
In Najal Balagha, Imam Ali says, Honor lies

306
00:09:31,470 --> 00:09:33,430
in the heart, not in the position.

307
00:09:34,090 --> 00:09:36,130
We even see the same principle highlighted in

308
00:09:36,130 --> 00:09:37,850
the modern era by the Aga Khan IV,

309
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:40,490
who told his community that knowledge is honored

310
00:09:40,490 --> 00:09:42,930
not because of the diplomas it grants, but

311
00:09:42,930 --> 00:09:44,870
because of what it makes a person do.

312
00:09:44,870 --> 00:09:48,770
The metric is internal action, not external validation.

313
00:09:49,430 --> 00:09:50,670
It is like we are all playing a

314
00:09:50,670 --> 00:09:53,490
massive multiplayer game, obsessing over our public stats,

315
00:09:53,610 --> 00:09:54,930
our followers, our job titles.

316
00:09:55,490 --> 00:09:56,990
Hatim looked at the game and realized the

317
00:09:56,990 --> 00:09:58,230
server was going to shut down eventually.

318
00:09:58,510 --> 00:10:00,450
So he started playing by the only metric

319
00:10:00,450 --> 00:10:01,810
the developer actually tracks.

320
00:10:02,050 --> 00:10:03,250
That's a great way to put it.

321
00:10:03,570 --> 00:10:05,610
But you know, playing by a different metric

322
00:10:05,610 --> 00:10:07,970
puts you wildly out of sync with everyone

323
00:10:07,970 --> 00:10:10,730
else, which brings up a massive psychological friction.

324
00:10:11,050 --> 00:10:12,150
Which is the fifth benefit.

325
00:10:12,370 --> 00:10:12,610
Yeah.

326
00:10:12,610 --> 00:10:14,570
And this is a trap that consumes almost

327
00:10:14,570 --> 00:10:14,990
everyone.

328
00:10:15,910 --> 00:10:16,210
Envy.

329
00:10:17,170 --> 00:10:19,510
Hatim looks at people and sees them complaining

330
00:10:19,510 --> 00:10:23,550
about each other, harboring intense jealousy and fighting

331
00:10:23,550 --> 00:10:25,770
out of a constant competition for greatness and

332
00:10:25,770 --> 00:10:26,270
possessions.

333
00:10:26,410 --> 00:10:28,690
So Hatim meditated on a verse in the

334
00:10:28,690 --> 00:10:31,530
Quran where God says, It is we who

335
00:10:31,530 --> 00:10:33,910
distribute their means of livelihood among them in

336
00:10:33,910 --> 00:10:34,850
the life of this world.

337
00:10:35,330 --> 00:10:38,090
He realized that the distribution of provision had

338
00:10:38,090 --> 00:10:39,050
already happened.

339
00:10:39,050 --> 00:10:41,630
The allocation of resources was decided by God

340
00:10:41,630 --> 00:10:43,550
long before any of us arrived on the

341
00:10:43,550 --> 00:10:43,770
scene.

342
00:10:43,870 --> 00:10:44,210
Exactly.

343
00:10:44,630 --> 00:10:47,670
Because the distribution is already set, competing with

344
00:10:47,670 --> 00:10:49,550
someone else doesn't actually change the outcome.

345
00:10:50,090 --> 00:10:52,870
Once Hatim internalized this fact, he simply let

346
00:10:52,870 --> 00:10:54,170
people have what they had been given.

347
00:10:54,370 --> 00:10:56,010
He knew his own provision came from the

348
00:10:56,010 --> 00:10:57,030
exact same hand.

349
00:10:57,150 --> 00:10:59,190
Okay, but cognitively, how do you actually do

350
00:10:59,190 --> 00:10:59,430
that?

351
00:10:59,490 --> 00:11:01,630
I mean, when your coworker gets the promotion

352
00:11:01,630 --> 00:11:03,750
you worked years for, you can tell yourself

353
00:11:03,750 --> 00:11:05,550
that God ordained it, but your heart is

354
00:11:05,550 --> 00:11:06,050
still burning.

355
00:11:06,150 --> 00:11:06,690
It is, yeah.

356
00:11:06,690 --> 00:11:09,430
And if you truly believe the distribution is

357
00:11:09,430 --> 00:11:11,490
fixed, doesn't that just kill ambition?

358
00:11:12,230 --> 00:11:14,610
Doesn't it invite a total passivity where you

359
00:11:14,610 --> 00:11:16,630
sit back and say, well, whatever is meant

360
00:11:16,630 --> 00:11:18,330
for me will find me, so why even

361
00:11:18,330 --> 00:11:18,770
try?

362
00:11:19,450 --> 00:11:22,050
That's a really common pushback, but it kills

363
00:11:22,050 --> 00:11:23,290
envy, not action.

364
00:11:23,810 --> 00:11:26,310
The discipline isn't to stop moving or stop

365
00:11:26,310 --> 00:11:26,650
building.

366
00:11:27,330 --> 00:11:29,510
The discipline is to control where you look

367
00:11:29,510 --> 00:11:30,390
while you work.

368
00:11:30,870 --> 00:11:33,370
You still labor, but you stop looking sideways

369
00:11:33,370 --> 00:11:34,950
at your neighbor's plate to see if they

370
00:11:34,950 --> 00:11:35,450
got more.

371
00:11:35,450 --> 00:11:36,390
Oh, that makes sense.

372
00:11:36,410 --> 00:11:36,570
Yeah.

373
00:11:36,790 --> 00:11:39,470
And the Prophet Muhammad outlined the exact psychological

374
00:11:39,470 --> 00:11:41,150
grounding exercise for this.

375
00:11:41,730 --> 00:11:43,650
He instructed his followers to look at those

376
00:11:43,650 --> 00:11:46,210
who are below them in worldly provision and

377
00:11:46,210 --> 00:11:47,510
not to look at those who are above

378
00:11:47,510 --> 00:11:47,810
them.

379
00:11:48,370 --> 00:11:50,090
He said that looking downward is more likely

380
00:11:50,090 --> 00:11:52,110
to keep a person from belittling the blessings

381
00:11:52,110 --> 00:11:53,250
of Allah upon them.

382
00:11:53,590 --> 00:11:56,090
It forces an immediate recalibration of gratitude.

383
00:11:56,850 --> 00:11:58,630
By looking at those who have less, you

384
00:11:58,630 --> 00:12:01,210
properly define the massive size of the blessings

385
00:12:01,210 --> 00:12:04,070
you already hold, which just extinguishes the fire

386
00:12:04,070 --> 00:12:04,550
of envy.

387
00:12:04,550 --> 00:12:05,170
It does.

388
00:12:05,290 --> 00:12:06,710
And when you stop seeing your neighbor as

389
00:12:06,710 --> 00:12:08,590
a competitor for a finite slice of the

390
00:12:08,590 --> 00:12:11,210
pie, it completely dismantles how you view enemies,

391
00:12:11,370 --> 00:12:13,230
which brings us to the sixth benefit.

392
00:12:13,590 --> 00:12:16,310
Hatim looks around and sees everyone holding on

393
00:12:16,310 --> 00:12:18,010
to enmities against each other.

394
00:12:18,190 --> 00:12:20,710
People exhaust themselves plotting against their rivals.

395
00:12:21,370 --> 00:12:22,710
But then he looks at the Quran and

396
00:12:22,710 --> 00:12:25,170
he realizes there is only one named enemy.

397
00:12:25,390 --> 00:12:25,670
Yes.

398
00:12:26,170 --> 00:12:28,990
The Quran says, Verily, Satan is your enemy,

399
00:12:29,210 --> 00:12:30,450
so treat him as your enemy.

400
00:12:30,950 --> 00:12:33,370
That is the verse Hatim anchors himself to.

401
00:12:33,990 --> 00:12:37,070
Humanity was commanded not to worship Satan, who

402
00:12:37,070 --> 00:12:38,070
is the open enemy.

403
00:12:38,870 --> 00:12:41,350
Hatim realized that fighting other humans was just

404
00:12:41,350 --> 00:12:43,190
a distraction from the actual war.

405
00:12:43,430 --> 00:12:45,670
Just think about the profound relief of that

406
00:12:45,670 --> 00:12:46,270
realization.

407
00:12:46,830 --> 00:12:48,630
The person at work who undermines you, the

408
00:12:48,630 --> 00:12:51,050
neighbor who annoys you, the people who actively

409
00:12:51,050 --> 00:12:52,330
oppose your worldview.

410
00:12:52,910 --> 00:12:53,870
They are just people.

411
00:12:54,030 --> 00:12:55,710
They are human beings doing their thing, driven

412
00:12:55,710 --> 00:12:58,150
by their own anxieties, mostly without even thinking

413
00:12:58,150 --> 00:12:58,690
about you.

414
00:12:58,830 --> 00:12:59,270
Exactly.

415
00:12:59,490 --> 00:13:01,490
The real enemy is the internal voice telling

416
00:13:01,490 --> 00:13:02,150
you to hate them.

417
00:13:02,770 --> 00:13:05,050
If you could fully internalize that no human

418
00:13:05,050 --> 00:13:07,550
being is your actual enemy, the emotional weight

419
00:13:07,550 --> 00:13:09,190
that drops off your shoulders is staggering.

420
00:13:09,410 --> 00:13:11,370
It clears the psychological path entirely.

421
00:13:11,810 --> 00:13:13,890
And that clearing leads to a logical step

422
00:13:13,890 --> 00:13:14,850
in the seventh benefit.

423
00:13:15,410 --> 00:13:17,730
Once you stop fighting enemies, the only anxiety

424
00:13:17,730 --> 00:13:18,970
left is raw survival.

425
00:13:19,250 --> 00:13:20,190
Because we all have to eat.

426
00:13:20,490 --> 00:13:20,750
Right.

427
00:13:21,230 --> 00:13:24,670
Hatim observed people humiliating themselves and engaging in

428
00:13:24,670 --> 00:13:28,410
doubtful, even forbidden earnings, out of a sheer

429
00:13:28,410 --> 00:13:30,330
panic to secure their sustenance.

430
00:13:30,770 --> 00:13:33,330
They were terrified of starving, so they compromised

431
00:13:33,330 --> 00:13:35,030
their integrity just to make sure they had

432
00:13:35,030 --> 00:13:35,430
enough.

433
00:13:35,970 --> 00:13:37,670
So what verse did he anchor himself to

434
00:13:37,670 --> 00:13:38,210
for this one?

435
00:13:38,730 --> 00:13:41,050
He anchored himself in the Quranic promise that

436
00:13:41,050 --> 00:13:43,070
there is no living creature on earth whose

437
00:13:43,070 --> 00:13:45,950
sustenance is not the absolute responsibility of God.

438
00:13:46,270 --> 00:13:49,230
He recognized himself as a living creature, meaning

439
00:13:49,230 --> 00:13:51,030
that divine promise covered him.

440
00:13:51,430 --> 00:13:52,830
Which again, we have to be careful not

441
00:13:52,830 --> 00:13:55,130
to misread this as an excuse for laziness.

442
00:13:55,510 --> 00:13:57,050
Hatim is not suggesting you sit in a

443
00:13:57,050 --> 00:13:58,790
room and wait for food to magically appear.

444
00:13:58,950 --> 00:13:59,630
No, not at all.

445
00:13:59,630 --> 00:14:01,250
He is stating that you do not violate

446
00:14:01,250 --> 00:14:03,670
the moral law, the sharia, to chase what

447
00:14:03,670 --> 00:14:05,370
God has already promised to provide.

448
00:14:05,710 --> 00:14:08,710
The prophet beautifully illustrated the mechanics of this

449
00:14:08,710 --> 00:14:10,750
reliance with the example of the birds.

450
00:14:11,350 --> 00:14:13,390
He said if you truly relied on God,

451
00:14:13,890 --> 00:14:15,730
he would provide for you as he provides

452
00:14:15,730 --> 00:14:16,310
for the birds.

453
00:14:16,930 --> 00:14:18,750
They leave their nests in the morning hungry,

454
00:14:19,150 --> 00:14:20,770
and they return in the evening full.

455
00:14:21,130 --> 00:14:22,510
They still have to fly out of the

456
00:14:22,510 --> 00:14:23,930
nest and scour the earth for food.

457
00:14:24,330 --> 00:14:25,410
They definitely go to work.

458
00:14:25,410 --> 00:14:28,190
But they leave the nest without the panic

459
00:14:28,190 --> 00:14:29,790
that they will not be provided for.

460
00:14:30,530 --> 00:14:32,970
They work without the crippling anxiety that the

461
00:14:32,970 --> 00:14:35,110
provision isn't out there waiting for them.

462
00:14:35,510 --> 00:14:38,690
Working without panic requires trusting that the floor

463
00:14:38,690 --> 00:14:40,190
will not fall out from under you.

464
00:14:40,690 --> 00:14:42,590
And that brings us to the culmination of

465
00:14:42,590 --> 00:14:44,890
Hatim's method, the eighth benefit.

466
00:14:45,110 --> 00:14:46,210
Yes, the final pivot.

467
00:14:47,010 --> 00:14:50,490
Hatim observed people relying on profoundly fragile things.

468
00:14:51,030 --> 00:14:53,010
Some trust their bank accounts, some trust their

469
00:14:53,010 --> 00:14:55,250
social networks, some trust their physical health.

470
00:14:55,870 --> 00:14:58,450
But he chooses to place his absolute reliance

471
00:14:58,450 --> 00:14:59,650
on God alone.

472
00:15:00,310 --> 00:15:01,930
This is the concept of tawakkol.

473
00:15:02,130 --> 00:15:04,210
And this isn't just a warm, comforting sentiment

474
00:15:04,210 --> 00:15:05,890
you put on a piece of calligraphy on

475
00:15:05,890 --> 00:15:06,310
your wall.

476
00:15:06,450 --> 00:15:06,570
No.

477
00:15:06,730 --> 00:15:09,810
This was the fundamental, load-bearing architecture of

478
00:15:09,810 --> 00:15:11,470
every single decision Hatim made.

479
00:15:11,870 --> 00:15:13,170
We should probably just let that sit for

480
00:15:13,170 --> 00:15:13,430
a second.

481
00:15:13,550 --> 00:15:13,770
Yeah.

482
00:15:14,110 --> 00:15:17,310
So, Shakiko Balki, the teacher who moments ago

483
00:15:17,310 --> 00:15:20,050
was grieving the loss of 33 years, listens

484
00:15:20,050 --> 00:15:21,270
to these eight pivots.

485
00:15:21,700 --> 00:15:24,530
He hears his student explain who he loves,

486
00:15:24,890 --> 00:15:27,770
who controls his appetites, where his wealth goes,

487
00:15:28,170 --> 00:15:30,970
how he measures honor, why he stops envying,

488
00:15:31,190 --> 00:15:33,310
who the real enemy is who feeds him,

489
00:15:33,470 --> 00:15:35,550
and who he ultimately relies on.

490
00:15:35,730 --> 00:15:37,730
And Shakiko doesn't just say, oh, good summary.

491
00:15:37,970 --> 00:15:38,230
No.

492
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:40,790
He says, oh, Hatim, may Allah grant you

493
00:15:40,790 --> 00:15:42,870
the success to do righteous deeds and walk

494
00:15:42,870 --> 00:15:43,530
on his path.

495
00:15:43,950 --> 00:15:45,530
You have told us very good things.

496
00:15:45,810 --> 00:15:47,350
I have seen in the Torah, in the

497
00:15:47,350 --> 00:15:49,130
Gospel, in the Psalms, and in the Holy

498
00:15:49,130 --> 00:15:51,390
Qur'an that all four of these books

499
00:15:51,390 --> 00:15:52,810
name these eight benefits.

500
00:15:53,330 --> 00:15:55,410
Whoever acts on these eight has acted on

501
00:15:55,410 --> 00:15:56,430
all four books.

502
00:15:56,570 --> 00:15:58,590
The Torah, the Gospel, the Psalms, and the

503
00:15:58,590 --> 00:15:58,950
Qur'an.

504
00:15:59,430 --> 00:16:01,430
Why would these specific eight pivots be the

505
00:16:01,430 --> 00:16:04,170
central heartbeat of every revealed scripture across all

506
00:16:04,170 --> 00:16:04,830
of human history?

507
00:16:05,050 --> 00:16:06,410
It's an incredible statement.

508
00:16:06,490 --> 00:16:08,510
It is a staggering claim about the universal

509
00:16:08,510 --> 00:16:10,010
architecture of spiritual survival.

510
00:16:10,350 --> 00:16:11,890
We are going to leave that mystery intact

511
00:16:11,890 --> 00:16:12,690
for you to sit with.

512
00:16:12,890 --> 00:16:13,410
Why these eight?

513
00:16:13,510 --> 00:16:15,570
Imam al-Ghazali ends his retelling of the

514
00:16:15,570 --> 00:16:17,350
story with a direct sentence to his former

515
00:16:17,350 --> 00:16:17,770
student.

516
00:16:17,770 --> 00:16:21,930
Ghazali writes, my dear beloved son, you now

517
00:16:21,930 --> 00:16:23,550
know from this story that you do not

518
00:16:23,550 --> 00:16:24,790
need a lot of knowledge.

519
00:16:25,290 --> 00:16:27,330
You just need these eight pivots.

520
00:16:27,650 --> 00:16:29,590
Ask yourself, if you were to pick just

521
00:16:29,590 --> 00:16:32,190
one of Hatim's eight benefits to act as

522
00:16:32,190 --> 00:16:34,790
the architecture for your choices tomorrow morning, which

523
00:16:34,790 --> 00:16:36,850
one exposes the biggest illusion in your life

524
00:16:36,850 --> 00:16:37,230
right now?

525
00:16:37,510 --> 00:16:39,310
Wishing you peace and clarity as you consider

526
00:16:39,310 --> 00:16:39,570
that.
